data.content:
## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Pattern inventory in your code

| Line | API | Pattern |
|------|-----|---------|
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | catch block | Cleanup on abort — migrate to `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | ResetAbort | Continue loop after abort — use `IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Thread.Abort | Force-stop — replace with `cts.Cancel()` |
| `volatile bool _running` | loop flag | Cancellable work loop — replace with `CancellationToken` |

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime **cannot** forcibly inject a `ThreadAbortException`. Your `Stop()` method will crash, and even if you suppress the error, the thread will never stop if `GetNextItem()` is blocking.

---

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort equivalent needed. The while-loop condition
                // will exit naturally since the token is cancelled.
                // If you want to CONTINUE processing remaining items
                // (like ResetAbort did), break out selectively instead.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals all token checks and unblocks waiting calls

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. With cooperative cancellation,
            // this means GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
            // Log a warning — you cannot force-kill managed threads in .NET 8.
            Console.Error.WriteLine("Worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Key changes explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitOne`, `Task.Delay`); a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal — `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids catching unrelated OCEs from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | Loop condition `!token.IsCancellationRequested` handles continuation naturally |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` in Stop | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Join actually waits for the thread; Sleep just hopes it finishes |

---

### Critical pitfall: `GetNextItem()` must cooperate

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or socket), cancellation **will not interrupt it** unless you pass the token through. This is the #1 migration failure:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks forever, ignoring cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take() — no token
}

// AFTER: wakes up when cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}

// If using a raw WaitHandle or ManualResetEvent:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Replace: _signal.WaitOne();
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

### Other pitfalls to watch for

1. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** — it leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed. The `IDisposable` pattern above handles this.

2. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — if you catch it in `ProcessLoop`, that's fine (top-level orchestration), but don't catch and suppress it inside `ProcessItem` or helper methods. Let it propagate.

3. **No force-kill equivalent exists** — if uncooperative code truly cannot be modified (e.g., third-party native call), move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no managed thread equivalent.

4. **`Thread.Sleep` in worker code** — replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so the sleep is interruptible:
   ```csharp
   // BEFORE: sleeps for 5s, ignoring cancellation
   Thread.Sleep(5000);

   // AFTER: wakes immediately on cancellation
   token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(5000);
   ```
